Trix index on the Cadeau dominio

The TRIX index is based on four state variables (n ), which are directly related to productivity: chlorophyll a (Chl, mg/m3 ), oxygen as the absolute percentage deviation from oxygen saturation (DO, %), dissolved inorganic nitrogen (DIN, mg/m3, and total phosphorous (TP, mg/m3. In particular, DIND N-NO3 C N-NO2 C N-NH4 and DOD |100- Ox | , where Ox is the oxygen saturation. Each state variable is scaled by the highest (Ui ) and the lowest (Li ) values in the data time series, and TRIX is defined as

\[TRIX= \frac {k}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n\frac{(logM_i-logL_i)}{(logU_i-logL_i)} \] The TRIX index was developed b Vollenweider et al. (1992)

E. Fiori et al.: Trophic index (TRIX) values for the Adriatic Sea basin

TRIX units Conditions Trophic state
0–4 Oligotrophic Elevated
4–5 Good
5–6 Mediocre
6–10 Eutrophic Bad

In addition to TRIX, an efficiency coefficient can also be defined (Giovanardi and Vollenweider, 2004) as the logarithm of the ratio between the two aggregated main components of the TRIX. The efficiency coefficient can be considered a supplementary index with which to evaluate the nutrient utilization of the system.

\[eff.coeff= log\biggl( \frac{Chl \times Do}{DIN \times TP}\biggl)\]
